# Prayer HTML Conventions

## Source of Truth

Edit `/en/` first, then propagate the same structural changes to `/fr/`, `/ar/`, and `/fr-lsg/`. Only text content and `lang`/`dir` attributes differ between languages.

## Page Structure

```
<main class="container">
  <div class="hour-header"> ... </div>
  <div class="prayer-content">
    <div class="ornament"> ✝ ✝ ✝ </div>
    <section class="section">
      <h2 class="section-title">Section Name</h2>
      <div class="prayer-text">...</div>
    </section>
    ...
  </div>
  <nav class="nav-hours"> ... </nav>
</main>
```

## Key Classes

| Class | Usage |
|---|---|
| `.section` | Wraps each prayer section |
| `.section-title` | `<h2>` heading inside each section (used by JS for dropdown nav) |
| `.prayer-text` | Regular prayer paragraphs |
| `.psalm-verse` | Psalm verses |
| `.drop-cap` | First-letter drop cap on opening paragraphs |
| `.alleluia` | Highlighted "ALLELUIA" text |
| `.doxology` | Two-column Coptic/translation layout |
| `.ornament` | Decorative cross dividers between sections |

## Common Sections

Shared prayers (intro, Lord's Prayer, thanksgiving, Psalm 50, conclusion) are loaded by JS. Mark the container with `data-common-section="section-name"` instead of duplicating content.

## Midnight Hour

Uses watch-specific IDs: `gospel-watch1`, `gospel-watch2`, `gospel-watch3` for the jump-to-gospel feature.

## Navigation

Bottom nav (`.nav-hours`) links to all 11 hour pages. Hour dropdown and section dropdown live in `.sticky-subheader`.
